<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Fibonacci Number</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/IntegerSequences/Fibonac=
ciNumber.nb" download=3D"FibonacciNumber.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=
=3D"27" alt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The Fibonacci numbers are the sequence of numbers <img src=3D"https://mathw=
orld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inl=
ineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"=
52" height=3D"23" alt=3D"{F_n}_(n=3D1)^infty"> defined by the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://mathworld.wolfram.com/LinearRecurrenceEquation.html">linear
 recurrence equation</a>
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/FibonacciNumber/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequat=
ion" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"117" he=
ight=3D"20" alt=3D" F_n=3DF_(n-1)+F_(n-2) "></td><td align=3D"right" width=
=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn1" class=3D"eqnum">
(1)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
with <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNu=
mber/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"87" height=3D"21" alt=3D"F_1=3DF_2=3D1">.
 As a result of the definition (<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Fi=
bonacciNumber.html#eqn1">1</a>), it is conventional to define
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber=
/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:10=
0%" border=3D"0" width=3D"48" height=3D"22" alt=3D"F_0=3D0">.
</p>
<p>
The Fibonacci numbers for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/=
equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max=
-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D=
"n=3D1">, 2, ... are 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://=
oeis.org/A000045">A000045</a>).
</p>
<p>
Fibonacci numbers can be viewed as a particular case of the <a href=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/FibonacciPolynomial.html">Fibonacci polynomials</=
a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumb=
er/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:=
100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"41" height=3D"21" alt=3D"F_n(x)">
 with <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciN=
umber/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"80" height=3D"21" alt=3D"F_n=3DF_n(1)">.
</p>
<p>
Fibonacci numbers are implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/=
language/">Wolfram
Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Fi=
bonacci.html">Fibonacci</a></tt>[<i>n</i>].
</p>
<p>
The Fibonacci numbers are also a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/L=
ucasSequence.html">Lucas sequence</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"74" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"U_n(1,-1)">, and are companions to the <a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/LucasNumber.html">Lucas numbers</a> (which satisfy the =
same <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RecurrenceEquation.html">recu=
rrence
 equation</a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/gifs/FoxTrot20051011.jpg" =
class=3D"" style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"600" alt=3D"F=
oxTrot by Bill Amend">
</div>
<p>
The above cartoon (Amend 2005) shows an unconventional sports application o=
f the Fibonacci numbers (left two panels). (The right panel instead applies=
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PerrinSequence.html">Perrin
 sequence</a>).
</p>
<p>
A scrambled version 13, 3, 2, 21, 1, 1, 8, 5 (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.o=
rg/A117540">A117540</a>) of the first eight Fibonacci numbers appear as one=
 of the clues left by murdered
 museum curator Jacque Sauni=C3=A8re in D.&nbsp;Brown's novel <i><a href=3D=
"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1400079179/ref=3Dnosim/ericstreasur=
etro">The
 Da Vinci Code</a></i> (Brown 2003, pp.&nbsp;43, 60-61, and 189-192). In th=
e Season
 1 episode "<a href=3D"http://www.tv.com/numb3rs/episode/398596/summary.htm=
l">Sabotage</a>"
 (2005) of the television crime drama <i><a href=3D"http://www.amazon.com/e=
xec/obidos/ASIN/B000ERVJKE/ref=3Dnosim/ericstreasuretro">NUMB3RS</a></i>,
 math genius Charlie Eppes mentions that the Fibonacci numbers are found in=
 the structure
 of crystals and the spiral of galaxies and a nautilus shell. In the Season=
 4 episode
 "Masterpiece" (2008) of the CBS-TV crime drama "Criminal Minds,"
 the agents of the FBI Behavioral Analysis Unit are confronted by a serial =
killer
 who uses the Fibonacci sequence to determine the number of victims for eac=
h of his
 killing episodes. In this episode, character Dr.&nbsp;Reid also notices th=
at locations
 of the killings lie on the graph of a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/GoldenSpiral.html">golden spiral</a>,
 and going to the center of the spiral allows Reid to determine the locatio=
n of the
 killer's base of operations.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/gifs/FibonacciSequenceBina=
ryPlot.jpg" class=3D"" style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"5=
23" alt=3D"Binary plot of the Fibonacci sequence">
</div>
<p>
The plot above shows the first 511 terms of the Fibonacci sequence represen=
ted in binary, revealing an interesting pattern of hollow and filled triang=
les (Pegg 2003).
 A fractal-like series of white triangles appears on the bottom edge, due i=
n part
 to the fact that the binary representation of <img src=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline8.svg" class=3D"inline=
formula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"54"=
 height=3D"23" alt=3D"F_(2^n+2^(n+1))"> ends in <img src=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlin=
eformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"37=
" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n+2"> zeros. Many other similar properties exist.
</p>
<p>
The Fibonacci numbers give the number of pairs of rabbits <img src=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline10.svg" cla=
ss=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" =
width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> months after a single pair begins bree=
ding (and newly born
 bunnies are assumed to begin breeding when they are two months old), as fi=
rst described
 by Leonardo of Pisa (also known as Fibonacci) in his book <i>Liber Abaci.<=
/i> Kepler
 also described the Fibonacci numbers (Kepler 1966; Wells 1986, pp.&nbsp;61=
-62 and
 65). Before Fibonacci wrote his work, the Fibonacci numbers had already be=
en discussed
 by Indian scholars such as Gop=C4=81la (before 1135) and Hemachandra (c. 1=
150) who
 had long been interested in rhythmic patterns that are formed from one-bea=
t and two-beat
 notes or syllables. The number of such rhythms having <img src=3D"https://=
mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline11.svg" class=
=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" wi=
dth=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> beats altogether is <img src=3D"https://=
mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline12.svg" class=
=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" wi=
dth=3D"32" height=3D"22" alt=3D"F_(n+1)">, and hence these scholars both me=
ntioned the numbers
 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21, ... explicitly (Knuth 1997, p.&nbsp;80).
</p>
<p>
The numbers of Fibonacci numbers less than 10, <img src=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline13.svg" class=3D"inlin=
eformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"25=
" height=3D"21" alt=3D"10^2">, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/im=
ages/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline14.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"25" height=3D"21"=
 alt=3D"10^3">, ... are 6, 11, 16, 20, 25, 30, 35, 39, 44, ... (OEIS <a hre=
f=3D"http://oeis.org/A072353">A072353</a>). For <img src=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline15.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"3=
9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D1">, 2, ..., the numbers of decimal digits in <=
img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/I=
nline16.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"31" height=3D"22" alt=3D"F_(10^n)"> are 2, 21, 209=
, 2090, 20899, 208988, 2089877, 20898764,
 ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A068070">A068070</a>). As can be seen=
, the initial
 strings of digits settle down to produce the number 208987640249978733769.=
.., which
 corresponds to the decimal digits of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline17.svg" class=3D"inlineformula"=
 style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"146" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"lnphi=3D0.2089876..."> (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A097=
348">A097348</a>),
 where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Fibonacci=
Number/Inline18.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-w=
idth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">
 is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GoldenRatio.html">golden r=
atio</a>. This follows from the fact that
 for any power function <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/FibonacciNumber/Inline19.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-=
height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"52" height=3D"22" alt=3D"=
f_n=3Dc^n">, the number of decimal digits for <img src=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline20.svg" class=3D"inline=
formula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"29"=
 height=3D"22" alt=3D"f_(10^n)"> is given by <img src=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline21.svg" class=3D"inlinef=
ormula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"78" =
height=3D"23" alt=3D"10^nlog_(10)c">.
</p>
<p>
The Fibonacci numbers <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equa=
tions/FibonacciNumber/Inline22.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-he=
ight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"18" height=3D"21" alt=3D"F_=
n">,
 are <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Squareful.html">squareful</a>=
 for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNu=
mber/Inline23.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D6">, 12, 18, 24=
, 25, 30, 36, 42, 48, 50, 54, 56, 60, 66, ...,
 372, 375, 378, 384, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A037917">A037917<=
/a>) and
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Squarefree.html">squarefree</a> f=
or <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumb=
er/Inline24.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D1">, 2, 3, 4, 5, =
7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 13, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A037918">A037918<=
/a>).
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber=
/Inline25.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"48" height=3D"24" alt=3D"4|F_(6n)"> and <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline26=
.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bord=
er=3D"0" width=3D"64" height=3D"24" alt=3D"25|F_(25n)"> for all <img src=3D=
"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline27.sv=
g" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=
=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">, and there is at least one <img=
 src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inli=
ne28.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" =
border=3D"0" width=3D"54" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n&lt;=3D2m"> such that <img =
src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inlin=
e29.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" b=
order=3D"0" width=3D"43" height=3D"24" alt=3D"m|F_n">. No <a href=3D"https:=
//mathworld.wolfram.com/Squareful.html">squareful</a> Fibonacci
 numbers <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Fibonac=
ciNumber/Inline30.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"20" height=3D"24" alt=3D"F_p">
 are known with <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
FibonacciNumber/Inline31.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:1=
00%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p"> <a h=
ref=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PrimeNumber.html">prime</a>.
</p>
<p>
The ratios of successive Fibonacci numbers <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wo=
lfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNumber/Inline32.svg" class=3D"inlinefor=
mula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"61" he=
ight=3D"22" alt=3D"F_n/F_(n-1)"> approaches the <a href=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/GoldenRatio.html">golden
 ratio</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Fibon=
acciNumber/Inline33.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">
 as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/FibonacciNum=
ber/Inline34.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">
 approaches infinity, as first proved by Scottish mathematician Robert Sims=
on in 1753
 (Wells 1986, p.&nbsp;62). The ratios of alternate Fibonacci numbers are gi=
ven by
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Convergent.html">convergents<=
