00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi"> is the <a href=3D"=
https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GoldenRatio.html">golden ratio</a>, and
 are said to measure the fraction of a turn between successive leaves on th=
e stalk
 of a plant (<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Phyllotaxis.html">phy=
llotaxis</a>): for elm and linden, 1/3
 for beech and hazel, 2/5 for oak and apple, 3/8 for poplar and rose, 5/13 =
for willow
 and almond, etc. (Coxeter 1969, Ball and Coxeter 1987). The Fibonacci numb=
ers are
 sometimes called pine cone numbers (Pappas 1989, p.&nbsp;224). The role of=
 the Fibonacci
 numbers in botany is sometimes called Ludwig's law (Szymkiewicz 1928; Well=
s 1986,
 p.&nbsp;66; Steinhaus 1999, p.&nbsp;299). However, botanist Cooke suggests=
 caution
 in making correlations between botany and the Fibonacci sequence (Peterson=
 2006).
</p>
